{"author":{"id":"1949ffc23f11a8cb4f8c42a45c9ad241b49570df9a18687489e9ea78d87c54a3"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1772565676,"nonce":"7ByzgoeVzVknO+4flWBOOB2Tb+w=","title":"Studio: Option A — parametric composite nodes where outer params drive inner graph generation","message":"Currently (Option B implemented): composite node properties panel shows no inner-component\nparams. To edit internals, user enters the subgraph.\n\nOption A (future): outer params ARE the definition. Changing hidden_size on a Network node\nregenerates the inner graph from a template. Semantics: the outer node is a parameterized\nconstructor, not a view of pre-existing inner components.\n\n## Design\n\n- Each composite has a template function: (params) -\u003e GraphSpec\n- When params change on the outer node, the inner graph is regenerated via the template\n- Inner components are treated as derived from outer params, not independently editable\n- User can still enter the subgraph to inspect, but changes reset on next param change\n  (or: warn that inner graph has been manually edited and template application will overwrite)\n\n## Example\n\nNetwork(hidden_type=GRUCell, hidden_size=128, input_size=17, out_size=6)\n→ generates: GRUCell(hidden_size=128) → Linear(128→6) → Sigmoid\n\nChanging hidden_size to 256 on outer node regenerates the inner graph with the new size.\n\n## Note\n\nThis is distinct from Option B (now implemented). Option B is the correct default.\nOption A adds power for users who want to configure composites without entering them.\nOption A subsumes Option B — when Option A is implemented, Option B behavior is preserved\nfor composites with no exposed outer params.","files":null}]}